<h2>Gulls</h2>

<h3>Introduction</h3>

<p>
Gulls are seabirds belonging to the Laridae family. They can be found in many
parts of the world and are commonly seen near oceans, lakes and coastal areas.
Some species have also adapted very well to life near human cities.
</p>

<h3>Physical characteristics</h3>

<p>
Most gulls have white and gray feathers, long wings and webbed feet that make
them efficient swimmers. Their size can vary greatly depending on the species,
from smaller gulls to very large birds with impressive wingspans.
</p>

<h3>Behavior and feeding</h3>

<p>
Gulls are intelligent birds known for their adaptability. Their diet is very
diverse and may include fish, insects, shellfish and food leftovers found in
urban areas. They are also capable of using simple strategies to obtain food.
</p>

<h3>Life in groups</h3>

<p>
These birds usually live in colonies and communicate using a variety of calls
and body movements. Living in groups provides protection against predators and
helps them during nesting periods.
</p>
